Welcome to the pyMECP program!
This file discusses a particular aspect of the program. 
Please, consult the Manual for a detailed instruction on how to run pyMECP. 

The pyMECP program workflow is as follows:

1. Submit two single-point energy calculation jobs, JobN_A.inp and JobN_B.inp
2. Wait for both jobs to complete.
3. Update the next geometry based on the energy and gradients extracted from JobN_A.engrad and JobN_B.engrad files.
4. Submit new pair of jobs, JobN+1_A.inp and JobN+1_B.inp
5. Repeat steps 1-4 until convergence is reached (convergence criteria can be adjusted in TestConvergence.py if needed)

There are two options how the waiting time in Step 2 can be set.

Option 1. Fixed sleep time.
Allow for a fixed sleep time between two optimization steps (default). 
In this case search for the "# Wait for jobs to terminate" line in the sub_script.py file and set X in the "sleep(X)" line below
to the desired sleep time in seconds. For this option, it is highly recommended to run the first Job0_A.inp and Job0_B.inp jobs 
to estmate the average job_time. Then, for example, X could be set to ~ 1.5 * job_time.

Option 2. Monitor ORCA jobs in queue.
Allow Python to check if both jobs are terminaed in real time by checking the queue. 
Then, new jobs will be submitted right after both the previous jobs are terminated (queue is empty). 
To allow this option search for the "# Wait for submitted jobs" line in sub_script.py and uncomment 
the "#for jid in jobids:" and "#wait_for_job(jid)" lines below this line. Also, comment the "sleep(X)" line with the "#" sign. 
This option works fine, though we sometimes observed pyMECP stoped working without an error message, 
and strongly believe it was caused by some time update-related bugs in our HPC cluster. You could give it a try, and can always switch back to the option 1.

*** OPTIONAL ***
In the folder "test_heme" you can find output files for an example of finding the MECP between the lowest 
triplet and quintet states in Fe(II)-porphine molecule also known as heme. This example is covered in the 
Chapter 8 of the Manual. The "geom", "Input_Header_A", "Input_Header_B", "master_script.py", and "sub_script.py" 
files are currently adjusted for this example. You can use this example as a starting point for getting started with pyMECP. Good luck!
